result.execSummary:
The defendant Jimmy L Skenandore was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly conduct - domestic. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.
  • Disorderly Conduct. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
11:05 AM; Case called for Plea/sentencing hearing.  Defendant Jimmy L Skenandore in court.  Attorney John Scott Schiro in court for Jimmy L Skenandore. District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Niki Kane.  Atty. Schiro advises parties are prepared to resolve the matter by amending both counts to County Ordinance.  State confirms, noting that they will be asking the court order the DV surcharge in Count 1 but will allow defense to argue that it not be imposed. Atty. Schiro presents arguments and is asking the court to waive the DV surcharge.  Court will find defense has provided an offer of proof and will waive the DV surcharge in Count 1.  Prosecuting attorney moves to amend Count 1, with the DV enhancer, and 2, without the DV enhancer, to Disorderly Conduct contrary to ordinance 13-102(c)(8), Waukesha County Ordinances. Court approves amendment. No contest plea entered by Atty. Schiro on both Counts, Court will accept the pleas and finds the defendant guily of the Amended Count 1 & 2.  

COUNT 1:
The Court Orders the Following:
	
$267.50 (Court waived the DV surcharge) to be paid within 90 days. Failure to pay;  will result in a civil judgment.


COUNT 2:
The Court Orders the Following:
	
$267.50 to be paid within 90 days. Failure to pay;  will result in a civil judgment.
Plea/sentencing hearing on October 28, 2022 at 10:30 am.

1:44 PM; Case called for Hearing.  Prosecuting attorney Alyssa M Jay in court for the State of Wisconsin.   Defendant Jimmy L Skenandore in court.  Attorney John Scott Schiro in court for Jimmy L Skenandore.  Atty. Schiro provides an update, parties have reached a resolution but defendant needs time to complete a class. Atty. Schiro requests a plea and sentencing date in about 10 weeks.   State has no objection.  Court adjourns for plea and sentencing.
Plea/sentencing hearing scheduled for October 28, 2022 at 10:30 am.
Effective August 1, 2022, this case is assigned to Branch 7 Judicial Vacancy, pursuant to 22-SO-04(67).

08:49 AM Defendant Jimmy L Skenandore in court with attorney John Scott Schiro.  Christian Farina appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Atty. Schiro does not have discovery and asks for another status date.  State will send out discovery.  Court advised Atty. Schiro that if he wishes to proceed to Plea/Sentencing at the next date, a Plea Questionnaire needs to be filed in advance.  Hearing scheduled for August 19, 2022 at 01:30 pm.

Cash bail previously posted to be refunded to poster. Defendant to have no VIOLENT contact with victims A & B/witnesses A & B listed in the Criminal Complaint/Victim Identification Key.  Defendant is not to share, reproduce or distribute any personal and/or identifying information about the crime victim(s), except to their attorney.   Absolute sobriety, defendant is not to possess or consume any alcohol.

08:41 AM Defendant Jimmy L Skenandore in court with attorney Peter Heflin for attorney John Scott Schiro.  Andrew Nesheim appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Defense acknowledges receipt of complaint and waives reading of complaint.  
Service admitted/advised of charges and potential penalties.  
NOT GUILTY PLEA ENTERED BY COURT.  Hearing scheduled for July 6, 2022 at 08:30 am.
